body:
The `Display` behavior prior to this change always used a decimal format (like `%f`). With this PR, it uses either exponent or decimal depending on magnitude (like `%g`). I think that's the right default, which #24556 argues for, but it's also a rather largish breaking change that I didn't see mentioned above. `Display` can format `1e300`, which breaks the JSON serializer:

[JSON](https://github.com/rust-lang/rustc-serialize/blob/031333c08d4819aa36127f1a4070e3efcc2341d7/src/json.rs#L519):

``` rust
            let s = v.to_string();
            if s.contains(".") {s} else {s + ".0"}
```

`1e300.0` is not valid.

The CSV serializer works because `Display` in this PR reverts to decimal when a precision is specified:

[CSV](https://github.com/BurntSushi/rust-csv/blob/07fbf494f3d0c8a1cabf57ded2aa4b93dd171857/src/encoder.rs#L164):

``` rust
    let s: String = format!("{:.10}", v).trim_right_matches('0').into();
    if s.ends_with('.') { s + "0" } else { s }
```

@lifthrasiir hmm, it will probably be easier to land the most important parts of this PR (namely, the _bug fixes_) if you remove the big breaking change(s) like the one that @rprichard mentioned.

(Hopefully we could figure out a way for a user to opt-in to getting the `%g`-like behavior, either by adding a new format trait, or by changing the return type of the [precision method](http://doc.rust-lang.org/nightly/core/fmt/struct.Formatter.html#method.precision) and adding a new variant to its rule for `precision` in the [grammar](http://doc.rust-lang.org/nightly/std/fmt/index.html#syntax).)

But, I'll make sure we talk about this at the team meeting tonight.  Maybe we can go ahead and change this without going through an RFC.
